<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-503-537  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 503 537.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Oct 1 1990 v9 n21 p57(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GAO says DAB should oversee systems. (General Accounting Officeasks Defense Acquisition Board to oversee the Army's Unixapplications purchases)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Accounting OfficeGovernment ContractsUNIXUnited States. ArmyApplicationsMilitaryCommunications EquipmentUnited States. Defense Acquisition Board.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GAO Says DAB Should Oversee SystemsandM;The General Accounting Office has recommended that five Unix applications theArmy will set up on its new battlefield computer system be subjected tooversight all at once, rather than in pieces.andM;The five systems are part of the Army Tactical Command and Control System(ATCCS) that will run on the Common Hardware/Software suite of battlefieldcomputers supplied by contractor Miltope Corp.andM;The applications are fire support, maneuver control, air defense, combatsupport service, and intelligence and electronic warfare.andM;GAO said the Army has &quot;taken many appropriate actions to integrate the fiveATCCS applications and is working to resolve the technical problems itfaces.&quot;andP;  However, GAO said, the various projects are far enough along thatthey ought to be placed under the oversight of an independent authoritywithin the Defense Acquisition Board.andM;The DAB reports to the defense secretary and is the oversight authority forweapons systems.andP;  A committee within the DAB, the Major Automated InformationSystems Review Committee, provides oversight for civilian-style informationsystems but recently has been brought into the review process for strategicinformation systems.andM;Tactical systems like ATCCS remain categorized with the weapons they support,though several officials have said that regulations for software-intensivesystems ought to be the same regardless of the purpose being served.andM;GAO said the Army plans to integrate the five applications on three differentcommunications systems, compounding the need for an integrated ATTCS reviewscheme.andP;  Altogether, GAO said, the Army has estimated the cost of theunclassified sections of ATCCS at $20 billion.andM;GAO said Army officials call ATCCS &quot;a system of systems&quot; but have not yetdefined fully how the systems will interoperate.andP;  During the next three yearsor so, GAO reported, the Army and its contractors will be writing code forfour of the applications but have no overall ATCCS specifications to workwith -- unless a new oversight authority takes over.andM;GAO also said a communications workload study needs to be done so that theArmy can assure its commanders that information will be accessible to them onthe battlefield.andM;Since work on the ATCCS applications began, they have been overseenseparately, GAO said.andP;  Three have been approved by the DAB and two by theArmy's System Acquisition Review Council.andM;GAO's Information Management and Technology Division made its report, ArmyBattlefield Automation: Oversight Needed to Assure Integrated System, to Sen.andO;Daniel K. Inouye (D-Hawaii), chairman of the Senate Appropriations DefenseSubcommittee, and his House counterpart, Rep.andP;  John P. Murtha (D-Pa.).andO;</TEXT></DOC>